  "doc_id": "3333",
  "text": "Physiologically reduced FAF is seen in the absence of RPE cells (e.g., at the optic disc) or may be due to absorption of the incident short wavelength light by melanin, macular pigment, and the retinal vessels. 41 Reduced FAF in retinal diseases may be due to a number of factors, including photoreceptor and/or RPE cell loss, disrupted phagocytosis or disruption of the retinoid cycle. In areas of geographic atrophy of the RPE, a late form of age-related macular disease (AMD), FAF is intensely reduced. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] 43 Very recently, it has been shown that both rodand cone-driven sensitivity is reduced over such areas of decreased FAF in AMD, including geographic atrophy. 44 Loss of photoreceptors may also lead to reduced FAF, which may be expected because of several reasons. Progressive lipofuscin accumulation is mainly a byproduct of the constant phagocytosis of shed photoreceptor outer segment discs. [CITATION_3] 46 In humans, photoreceptor density was found to correlate with the lipofuscin concentration of the opposing RPE cells. 47 Moreover, it has been demonstrated that lipofuscin deposition decreased significantly in retinal degenerate rats only after photoreceptors were lost. 48 The residual bodies containing autofluorescent material have a finite half-life, because there is a constant degradation of residual bodies in the RPE. [CITATION_4] 50 Impaired outer segment phagocytosis or a disrupted retinoid cycle may also contribute to reduced FAF. Mutation of a receptor tyrosine kinase gene (MERTK), in the Royal College of Surgeons (RCS) rat results in defective phagocytosis of photoreceptor outer segments by the RPE and retinal degeneration. Mutations in MERTK cause RP in humans. 51 Despite the RPEspecific nature of the defect, photoreceptors are affected first, through the process of apoptosis 52 and the time course of photoreceptor degeneration is rapid. Vitamin A (retinoids) plays a key role in formation of lipofuscin in the RPE. It has been shown that formation of RPE lipofuscin fluorophores is almost completely dependent on a normal visual cycle, because absence of retinal (both all-trans and 11-cis) in RPE65-knockout mice drastically reduces the formation of lipofuscin fluorophores in such animals. 53 Thus, normal FAF is likely to reflect the anatomic integrity of both the RPE and the photoreceptors, normal outer segment turnover, and normal vitamin A metabolism.",
